# operation error index must match the number of prior dispatches

When testing reducer errors, the operation index matters:

```typescript
// First operation dispatched → index [0]
const doc1 = reducer(document, addItem({ id: "1", name: "test" }));

// Second operation dispatched → index [1]
const doc2 = reducer(doc1, addItem({ id: "1", name: "duplicate" }));
expect(doc2.operations.global[1].error).toBe("Duplicate ID");

// ❌ Wrong — index [0] is the first (successful) operation
expect(doc2.operations.global[0].error).toBe("Duplicate ID");
```

The index corresponds to the total number of operations dispatched, not the number of errors. Since [[operation errors are recorded on operations not thrown to callers]], every dispatch (successful or failed) produces an operation at the next index.

